"""# Analyst Sentiment and Recommendation

Now that we have visualized and conducted analysis on either a certain stock or handful of potential portfolio-based stocks, we should move on to some market sentiment to dive deeper.

In order to understand the sentiment analysis from these corporations, it is important to uinderstand the terminology behind their ratings.  We will discuss here:


> Buy: Also known as strong buy and "on the recommended list." Needless to say, buy is a recommendation to purchase a specific security.

> Sell: Also known as strong sell, it's a recommendation to sell a security or to liquidate an asset.

> Neutral/Equal-Weight: Asset is expected to perform at the same pace as comparable companies or in-line with the market.


> Underperform/Underweight: Analyst recommendation that means a stock is expected to do slightly worse than the overall stock market return. 


> Outperform/Overweight: Analyst recommendation meaning a stock is expected to do slightly better than the market return.
"""

#Grabs specific stock user wishes to look at analyst recommendations for
#Wrap calculations within try and except to check if the entered input cannot be calculated
try:
    stock = (input("Enter user ticker here: \n"))
    is_string = stock.isalpha()
    if is_string == False:
        del stock
        
    #Displays message showing which stock we will be looking at
    print("We will be looking at sentiment around the "+ stock.upper() + ".\n")
    #Wrap calculations within try and except to check if the entered input cannot be calculated
    stock = yf.Ticker(stock)
    stock_recommendation = stock.recommendations

    #Grab the 5 latest reccomendations from the back of the data
    for i in range(1, 6):
        firm = stock_recommendation["Firm"][-i]
        grade = stock_recommendation["To Grade"][-i]
        date = stock_recommendation.index[-i].date()
        message = (f"The firm {firm} rated this security most recently as {grade} on {date}.\n")
        
        print(message)
except:
    print("The asset ticker you entered is either incorrect or we do not have the relevant data... Please Try again.")

def get_sentiment(tickers):
  for symbol in tickers:
    try:
      stock = symbol
      is_string = stock.isalpha()
      if is_string == False:
          del stock
          
      #Displays message showing which stock we will be looking at
      print("We will be looking at sentiment around the "+ stock.upper() + ".\n")
      #Wrap calculations within try and except to check if the entered input cannot be calculated
      stock = yf.Ticker(stock)
      stock_recommendation = stock.recommendations

      #Grab the 5 latest reccomendations from the back of the data
      for i in range(1, 6):
          firm = stock_recommendation["Firm"][-i]
          grade = stock_recommendation["To Grade"][-i]
          date = stock_recommendation.index[-i].date()
          message = (f"The firm {firm} rated this security most recently as {grade} on {date}.\n")
          print(message)
    except:
        print("The asset ticker you entered is either incorrect or we do not have the relevant data... Please Try again.")
    print('------------------------------------------')

stocks = ['CRM', 'TSLA']

get_sentiment(stocks)

"""#Understanding Financial Metrics

# Dividends

One of the most important and steady forms of income is the dividend.  This is a certain fixed dollar amount which the company returns to an investor.  Some companies use a very large dividend to attract investors, while others have a small divided, or even none at all! It is always important to factor in because it is one of the safest forms of income!

> ![Dividend Picture - Proj pic 1.png](data:image/png;base64,)
"""

symbol = 'AAPL'
stock = yf.Ticker(symbol)
stock_info = stock.info
stock_dividend = stock.dividends

#Calculate the day which you need the security before in order to qualify for the next dividend
day = stock_info['exDividendDate']
timestamp = datetime.datetime.fromtimestamp(day)
for k, v in stock_info.items():
    try:
        if k == "dividendRate":
            print(f"{symbol} pays a {round(v, 3)}% annual dividend.\n")
            for i in range(1, 2):
              payment = stock_dividend[-i]
              date = stock_dividend.index[-i].date()
              print(f"The most recent dividend was an ${payment} on {date}")
              print(f"If you purchase {symbol} before or on {timestamp.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')} then you will be paid the next dividend! ")

    except:
        print(f"{stock.upper()} does not pay a dividend at the moment.")

